<dl id="n11146h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11146h">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11146h"> 146(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Dr Achmed Borumborad ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n11146h"><li>FW 492.22 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n11146h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n11146h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n11146h">MS BL 47484a-12</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:113 <a name="rAd3" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rAd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd3.htm#n11146h">Draft: III&sect;3A.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The recent discussion about Turkish baths recalls to a correspondent their originator in Dublin, <mark>Dr. Achmet Borumborard</mark>, the first Turk who ever walked our streets in native costume. <font color="green">[...]</font> The doctor fell in love with a Miss Hartigan, who declined to marry him unless he shaved and became a Christian. He shaved, reappeared, fell upon his knees before her, and cried, &ldquo;Don&apos;t be angry, my dear creature! To tell the honest truth, I am as good a Christian as the Archbishop. I&apos;m your own countryman, Mr. Patrick Joyce from Kilkenny County&mdash;the devil a Turk any more than yourself.&rdquo; <small> <a name="FJ14jul24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FJ14jul24"><cite title="source">Freeman's Journal</cite></a> (14 July 1924) 8/6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Doctor Achmet Borumborad: the pseudonym of Mr Patrick Joyce, an eighteenth-century Dublin quack. His attraction lay in his hair. </mm> </dd></dl>
